2. Action layer (what the agent is allowed to do)
This is the action space – a schema of everything the agent can do on Windows. Each action is a structured JSON command that the model outputs.

Typical action categories:

Mouse actions

move_mouse(x, y)

click(x, y, button="left")

double_click(element_id)

Keyboard actions

type_text("hello")

press_keys(["ctrl", "c"])

Window management

focus_window("Untitled - Notepad")

close_window("Calculator")

resize_window("Notepad", x, y, width, height)

App launching

open_app("notepad.exe")

open_url("https://example.com")

System-level

open_file("C:/Users/you/Documents/todo.txt")

save_file()

take_screenshot()

Action schema example:

json
{
  "action_type": "click_element",
  "params": {
    "element_id": "edit_1"
  }
}
The agent must be trained or prompted to always respond with a JSON action or a structured list of actions, never free‑form “do this” text.

3. Orchestration layer (the control loop)
This is the “brainstem” that glues everything together. It is NOT the LLM itself; it’s the logic around it.

Core responsibilities:

Looping:

Capture observation from the environment

Build a prompt (or structured input) for the model

Send it to the model

Parse model output into actions

Execute actions via the action layer

Get updated observation

Repeat until done / timeout / success

State management:

Track task goal

Track step count, history of actions, and observations

Detect loops or stuck behavior

Safety & constraints:

Whitelist allowed actions (e.g., no delete_file, no shutdown)

Sandboxing (e.g., limit to specific apps or directories)

Rate limiting (avoid spam clicking or wild loops)

Retry and error handling:

If an action fails (element missing, app not available), feed explicit error back to the model as part of the next observation.

Pseudo‑loop:

python
while not done and steps < MAX_STEPS:
    obs = get_environment_state()
    prompt = build_prompt(task, obs, history)
    model_output = call_model(prompt)
    actions = parse_actions(model_output)

    for action in actions:
        result = execute_action(action)
        log(action, result)

    done = check_if_task_completed(task, obs, history)
    steps += 1
